Combining both populations, RV infections were seen all year round with a peak in incidence in the autumn and winter of 2010 (Fig. 3
). Fig. 4
shows that there is no distinct circulation pattern for the different RV types in time. Some trends could be observed. Type RV-A78, which was the most prevalent strain in the hospitalised population, was found only between July 2010 and July 2011. The second most prevalent type, RV-A12, was detected in the spring of 2010 and was sporadically detected again, but only in non-hospitalised children in the winter of 2011–2012. RV-C2, the most prevalent RV-C, was mainly observed during the autumn and the beginning of winter 2010–2011. In conclusion, despite small numbers no season-specific types could be observed.
